    "Examples of such algorithms include SaiyanH and GSPo described in Sects.",
    "4.2.1 and 4.2.2, respectively.",
    "Early work with hard constraints involved specifying features (arcs or edges) that were either required or prohibited in the learnt graph, or specifying a topological ordering that the learnt graph must be consistent with.",
    "De Campos and Castellano (2007) modified the score-based hill-climbing algorithm and the constraint-based PC algorithm to produce graphs consistent with hard constraints.",
    "Simulations involved specifying between 10 and 40% of possible required or prohibited features."
